"""
mkt-christ — Proverbs 25–27 (83 verses)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-proverbs-25-27.py
Ch25: Hezekiah's collection (v1); glory-of-God-to-conceal (v2 → Col 2:3; Matt 13:44);
  feed-your-enemy (v21-22) — direct quotation in Rom 12:20;
  good news from a distant land (v25 → gospel as euangelion);
  muddied spring (v26 → righteous-man-who-gives-way).
Ch26: Causeless curse (v2 → Gal 3:13); dog-returns-to-vomit (v11 → 2 Pet 2:22);
  digs-a-pit (v27 → Christ's resurrection overturns the trap).
Ch27: Enemy's kisses (v6 → Judas's betrayal kiss, Matt 26:48);
  iron-sharpens-iron (v17 → Heb 10:24-25); fig-tree-tender-honored (v18 → John 15);
  water-reflects-face (v19 → Heb 1:3: Son as exact representation).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "25": {
    "1": "<p>The theme: the Hezekiah scribal collection. Hezekiah&#8217;s copying of Solomon&#8217;s proverbs is a type of the preservation of divine wisdom through faithful human transmission. The NT applies the same pattern to Christ: &#8220;the Son, whom he has appointed heir of all things, through whom also he made the universe&#8221; (Heb 1:2) — the definitive Word preserved and proclaimed through the apostolic witness. The scribal work of preservation is itself a participation in the transmission of divine wisdom.</p>",
    "2": "<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;It is the glory of God to conceal things, but the glory of kings is to search them out.&#8221; The divine hiddenness that Proverbs acknowledges is the pattern that Christ both embodies and resolves. Paul says &#8220;in Christ are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&#8221; (Col 2:3) — the concealment of God&#8217;s wisdom is found to be hidden <em>in a person</em>. Jesus speaks in parables &#8220;because the knowledge of the secrets of the kingdom of heaven has been given to you&#8221; (Matt 13:11) — the concealed things are disclosed to those who receive the King.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The theme: the unsearchable heart of kings — as high as the heavens, as deep as the earth. The king&#8217;s inscrutable heart is the shadow of the divine inscrutableness that the NT applies to Christ: &#8220;Oh, the depth of the riches of the wisdom and knowledge of God! How unsearchable his judgments and his paths beyond tracing out!&#8221; (Rom 11:33). The king&#8217;s heart images the divine depth; Christ is the depth made accessible — &#8220;in him all the fullness of the Deity lives in bodily form&#8221; (Col 2:9).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme: removing dross to produce a vessel for the silversmith. The refining that produces a pure vessel is the pattern of divine purification that the prophets apply to Israel and the NT applies to the church: &#8220;he will sit as a refiner and purifier of silver&#8221; (Mal 3:3). Christ is both the refiner who purifies (Rev 3:18: &#8220;I counsel you to buy from me gold refined in the fire&#8221;) and the pure vessel himself — &#8220;a lamb without blemish or defect&#8221; (1 Pet 1:19).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The theme: removing the wicked from before the king establishes the throne in righteousness. The purified royal court is the shadow of the eschatological purification that Christ accomplishes: &#8220;he will separate the people from one another as a shepherd separates the sheep from the goats&#8221; (Matt 25:32). The righteousness of the throne depends on the removal of what corrupts it — the work of judgment that Christ performs at his return establishes the eternal throne of righteousness.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The theme: the warning against self-promotion in the king&#8217;s presence. The wisdom that holds back from claiming position anticipates Christ&#8217;s teaching: &#8220;For whoever exalts himself will be humbled, and whoever humbles himself will be exalted&#8221; (Matt 23:12). Christ himself is the pattern: &#8220;he did not consider equality with God something to be used to his own advantage; rather, he made himself nothing&#8221; (Phil 2:6-7). The wisdom of self-restraint before the king is the shadow of the self-emptying of the Son.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Come up here&#8221; — the invitation from the host is better than self-elevation. Jesus uses this as the principle of kingdom-entry in Luke 14:10-11: take the lowest seat and wait to be invited up. The parable of the banquet (Luke 14:7-11) is essentially this proverb applied to the kingdom. The guest who waits to be called up by the host is rewarded; the one who claims the high seat is displaced. Christ himself is the host who calls up: &#8220;Come up here&#8221; (Rev 4:1).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme: the warning against rushing into legal dispute. The person who hastily brings a case to court and is shamed by their neighbor embodies the opposite of the wise patience that Proverbs commends. Jesus&#8217; counsel in Matt 5:25 follows this precisely: &#8220;Settle matters quickly with your adversary who is taking you to court.&#8221; The wisdom of pre-litigation settlement is the shadow of the radical reconciliation that Christ teaches — resolve the dispute before it reaches the judge.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theme: arguing the case directly with the neighbor rather than disclosing secrets to others. The wisdom of direct confrontation rather than indirect reputation-damage is the basis of Jesus&#8217; teaching on interpersonal conflict: &#8220;go and show him his fault, just between the two of you&#8221; (Matt 18:15). The Proverbs principle of direct case-making becomes Christ&#8217;s explicit teaching on the process of reconciliation within the community of disciples.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The theme: the ill repute that follows the disclosure of secrets. The person who gossips about a neighbor&#8217;s secret bears a permanent reputation for untrustworthiness. This reflects the broader wisdom principle that speech has lasting consequences — every careless word is accountable (Matt 12:36-37: &#8220;you will have to give account on the day of judgment for every empty word you have spoken&#8221;). The permanent ill repute of the gossip is the shadow of the eschatological accounting for every word.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The theme: the word spoken at the right moment like golden apples in silver settings. The perfectly timed word — beautiful in itself, beautifully framed — is the OT anticipation of the Word made flesh who speaks with perfect timing: &#8220;the right word at the right time&#8221; is fulfilled in Christ who &#8220;spoke with authority&#8221; (Mark 1:22), who answered every question with precisely the words needed at exactly the right moment. The word-as-golden-apple is the shadow of the Word who is himself the treasure.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The theme: the wise reprover to an obedient ear — like fine gold jewelry. The value of honest rebuke received well is the OT pattern for the NT&#8217;s teaching on correction within the community of faith: &#8220;preach the word&#8230; correct, rebuke, and encourage&#8221; (2 Tim 4:2). Christ as the faithful reprover — &#8220;those whom I love I rebuke and discipline&#8221; (Rev 3:19) — is the fulfilment of the wise-reprover image. The obedient ear that receives reproof as gold is the disciple who accepts the Lord&#8217;s correction.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theme: the faithful messenger who refreshes the spirit of his master. The servant who delivers the message reliably and so refreshes those who sent him is a type of the apostolic messenger. More fundamentally, it is a type of Christ as the faithful messenger: &#8220;Therefore, holy brothers and sisters, who share in the heavenly calling, fix your thoughts on Jesus, whom we acknowledge as our apostle and high priest&#8221; (Heb 3:1). Christ is the Father&#8217;s faithful messenger who completes his commission and refreshes those who await him.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The theme: clouds and wind without rain — the one who boasts of a gift never given. The disappointment of the braggart who promises but does not deliver is the foil for Christ&#8217;s faithfulness: &#8220;For no matter how many promises God has made, they are &#8216;Yes&#8217; in Christ&#8221; (2 Cor 1:20). The cloud without rain is the anti-type of Christ who is the fulfillment of every divine promise — the living water who does not disappoint the thirsty soul (John 4:14).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The theme: patience persuading the ruler; the soft tongue breaking a bone. The paradox of power — that gentleness accomplishes what force cannot — anticipates the NT&#8217;s inversion of power: &#8220;the weakness of God is stronger than human strength&#8221; (1 Cor 1:25). Christ&#8217;s non-coercive authority &#8220;amazed&#8221; those who heard him (Matt 7:28-29) — his teaching persuaded not through force but through truth. The soft tongue of Proverbs 25:15 is the shadow of the Word who speaks and creation listens.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The theme: the restraint in honey-eating — sufficiency not excess. The principle of appropriate measure rather than maximum consumption applies spiritually to the reception of blessing: gluttony of gifts destroys the capacity to receive. Paul articulates the same principle from the other direction: &#8220;I have learned, in whatever state I am, to be content&#8221; (Phil 4:11). Christ himself demonstrates sufficiency-in-limitation: &#8220;foxes have dens and birds have nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head&#8221; (Matt 8:20).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The theme: keeping the foot rare in the neighbor&#8217;s house lest overstay cause loathing. The wisdom of not overextending welcome reflects the same social intelligence that Jesus demonstrates — he does not force his presence on those who reject him (Luke 9:5: &#8220;shake the dust off your feet&#8221;; Rev 3:20: he stands at the door and <em>knocks</em> rather than entering uninvited). The guest who overstays becomes a burden; Christ waits to be received.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theme: the false witness as a weapon — club, sword, arrow. The three-weapon description captures the comprehensive violence of false testimony. At Christ&#8217;s trial, false witnesses were brought against him (Matt 26:59-61) — the false testimony that the wisdom tradition warns against was the instrument of the Son of God&#8217;s condemnation. The one against whom false clubs and swords and arrows were deployed bore their wounds so that justice could be re-established.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The theme: the unreliable person in time of trouble — broken tooth, lame foot. The failure of support in the hour of crisis is the background against which Christ&#8217;s faithfulness stands: &#8220;Can a mother forget the baby at her breast? Though she may forget, I will not forget you!&#8221; (Isa 49:15). The disciples all fled at Jesus&#8217; arrest (Matt 26:56); Peter denied him (Matt 26:69-75). Yet Christ remained the unfailing support: &#8220;I will never leave you nor forsake you&#8221; (Heb 13:5).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: singing cheerful songs to a troubled heart — like vinegar on soda, like taking away a garment in cold. The wrong comfort at the wrong moment — inappropriate cheer imposed on grief — is the negative of the comfort that Christ offers: &#8220;Blessed are those who mourn, for they will be comforted&#8221; (Matt 5:4). The true Comforter (John 14:16-17, the Paraclete) meets the troubled heart with the right word; the false comforter of Proverbs 25:20 is the foil that makes genuine comfort visible.</p>",
    "21": "<p>A direct anticipation: &#8220;If your enemy is hungry, give him bread to eat; if he is thirsty, give him water to drink.&#8221; Paul quotes this verse directly in Rom 12:20 as the basis for Christian enemy-love. Jesus states the same principle as the kingdom-ethic in the Sermon on the Mount: &#8220;Love your enemies&#8230; pray for those who persecute you&#8221; (Matt 5:44). The Proverbs command to feed the enemy is the OT anticipation of the NT&#8217;s fullest expression of enemy-love — love that does not require the enemy to become a friend first.</p>",
    "22": "<p>A direct connection: &#8220;For you will heap burning coals on his head, and the LORD will reward you&#8221; — quoted verbatim by Paul in Rom 12:20 as the motivation for enemy-love. The burning coals are most likely a symbol of conviction or shame (not punishment) — the enemy fed by kindness is convicted rather than revenged. The LORD&#8217;s reward for enemy-love is the divine evaluation that overrides the social logic of retaliation. Christ himself is the supreme instance of this principle: his response to enemies is grace, not retribution.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The theme: the north wind bringing rain; the scowling face stopping slander. The natural cause-and-effect applied to social dynamics — certain responses reliably produce certain outcomes. The wisdom of understanding social cause-and-effect mirrors Christ&#8217;s own social wisdom: he knew &#8220;what was in each person&#8221; (John 2:25) and calibrated his responses accordingly. The verse participates in the broader theme that the created order and social order share the same underlying patterns of cause and consequence.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The theme: the better-than saying about domestic conflict. The roof-corner preference over a quarrelsome household reflects Proverbs&#8217; consistent valuation of peace over comfort. In the NT, Paul extends the principle: &#8220;if it is possible, as far as it depends on you, live at peace with everyone&#8221; (Rom 12:18). Christ comes to bring the deeper peace that the roof corner only symbolizes: &#8220;Peace I leave with you; my peace I give you. Not as the world gives do I give&#8221; (John 14:27).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The theme: good news from a distant land — like cold water to a thirsty soul. The <em>bĕśôrāh ṭôbāh</em> (good news) is the OT register for the NT&#8217;s <em>euangelion</em> (gospel). Isaiah uses the same vocabulary: &#8220;How beautiful on the mountains are the feet of those who bring good news (<em>bĕśôrāh</em>)&#8221; (Isa 52:7), applied in Rom 10:15 to the proclamation of Christ. The thirsty soul refreshed by distant good news is the image of every person who receives the gospel of Jesus Christ — the best news from the most distant source.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The theme: the righteous man who yields to the wicked is like a muddied spring. The pollution of a pure water source by the intrusion of what is dirty describes the corruption of justice when righteousness capitulates. This is precisely the failure that Pilate exemplifies at Jesus&#8217; trial — a man who &#8220;found no basis for a charge against him&#8221; (John 18:38) yet handed him over. The muddied spring is the emblem of compromised justice; Christ&#8217;s condemnation at the hands of compromised justice is the ultimate instance of this corruption.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The theme: the danger of seeking your own glory. &#8220;Nor is it glorious to seek your own glory&#8221; — the self-defeating character of self-promotion. Paul applies the same principle to the preaching of Christ: &#8220;For we do not preach ourselves, but Jesus Christ as Lord&#8221; (2 Cor 4:5). Christ himself as the pattern: &#8220;I do not accept glory from human beings&#8221; (John 5:41); &#8220;If I glorify myself, my glory means nothing&#8221; (John 8:54). The wisdom that refuses self-glory is enacted perfectly in Christ&#8217;s kenotic self-emptying.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The theme: the man without self-control is like a broken-down city without walls. The city wall as the metaphor for self-discipline — its absence leaves the person defenseless against attack. The NT applies this spatial vulnerability to spiritual warfare: &#8220;Put on the full armor of God, so that you can take your stand&#8221; (Eph 6:11). Christ is both the self-controlled one par excellence (who &#8220;in every way has been tempted, just as we are — yet he did not sin,&#8221; Heb 4:15) and the defense of those who lack self-control: the wall around the unprotected city.</p>"
  },
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>The theme: honor is out of place for a fool — like snow in summer. The incongruity of honoring the undeserving echoes the NT&#8217;s warnings about false teachers who receive honor they have not earned: &#8220;Many will say to me on that day, &#8216;Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name?&#8217;&#8221; (Matt 7:22). Christ&#8217;s own evaluation of honor is inverted from the world&#8217;s: the one who receives dishonor from the world receives honor from God (John 12:26), and the fool who receives earthly honor without wisdom has his reward already.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theme: a causeless curse does not land — like a fluttering sparrow. The curse that has no basis cannot achieve its purpose. The NT applies this principle to Christ himself: the curses and condemnations of his opponents could not establish his guilt because there was none. Peter declares: &#8220;you killed the author of life, but God raised him from the dead&#8221; (Acts 3:15). The causeless curse of the false accusers did not land permanently — resurrection invalidated every charge. Gal 3:13 reverses the logic: Christ became the curse <em>for us</em>, bearing what he had not earned.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The theme: the rod for the fool&#8217;s back — correction applied to those who will not receive verbal instruction. The appropriateness of the instrument to the recipient is the wisdom of proportionate discipline. Christ applies this principle in his ministry: some are healed by a word (Matt 8:8), others by touch (Mark 1:41), the marketplace merchants by a whip (John 2:15). The wisdom that matches the correction to the recipient characterizes Christ&#8217;s dealings with different people throughout the Gospels.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme: do not answer a fool according to his folly, lest you become like him. The paradox of vv4-5 (do not answer / do answer) reflects genuine wisdom about situational judgment. Jesus applies this situational wisdom in his responses: before Herod he stays silent (Luke 23:9); before Pilate he speaks (John 18:33-37); before the Pharisees he answers with questions (Matt 22:41-46). The wisdom of knowing when to engage and when to refuse engagement is demonstrated in Christ&#8217;s varied responses throughout his ministry.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The theme: answer a fool according to his folly, lest he think himself wise. The positive case for engagement — the fool whose error goes unchallenged will harden in self-deception. Jesus engages the Pharisees&#8217; trick questions not to avoid them but to expose the folly of their framing: &#8220;You are in error because you do not know the Scriptures or the power of God&#8221; (Matt 22:29). The answer that refutes the fool&#8217;s premise is itself a form of mercy — it removes the basis for the fool&#8217;s false confidence.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The theme: sending a message by a fool cuts off your own feet. The unreliable messenger destroys the sender&#8217;s purposes. Christ&#8217;s disciples are warned about this: &#8220;I am sending you out like sheep among wolves. Therefore be as shrewd as snakes and as innocent as doves&#8221; (Matt 10:16). The reliable messenger who carries the gospel faithfully is the opposite of the fool-messenger of Proverbs 26:6. Paul describes his own apostolic faithfulness in terms of not garbling the message: &#8220;unlike so many, we do not peddle the word of God for profit&#8221; (2 Cor 2:17).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The theme: the limp legs of the lame — a proverb in a fool&#8217;s mouth. The proverb without wisdom to apply it is not merely ineffective but visually undignified. Christ&#8217;s opponents who cite Scripture without understanding it (Matt 22:29: &#8220;you do not know the Scriptures or the power of God&#8221;) enact this principle precisely. The Sadducees&#8217; proof-text for their resurrection argument (v24-28) is the lame proverb in the fool&#8217;s mouth — right words, wrong application, producing a stumbling argument.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme: binding a stone in a sling — giving honor to a fool makes the honor useless and potentially dangerous. The stone in the sling cannot be thrown; the honor given to the fool cannot accomplish what honor is meant to accomplish. This reflects the consistent wisdom principle that social currency spent on the undeserving is wasted and corrupts the system. Christ restores honor to the dishonorable (the leper, the tax collector, the sinful woman) not as wasteful but as redemptive — he gives honor to those the world has dishonored.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theme: the thorn in the drunkard&#8217;s hand — a proverb in a fool&#8217;s mouth. The drunkard handling a thorn is both oblivious to pain and dangerous to others. The proverb in the fool&#8217;s mouth is similarly dangerous: familiar with the words but insensible to their meaning, he wields them carelessly. The NT applies the equivalent warning to those who handle Scripture carelessly: &#8220;they distort the Scriptures, to their own destruction&#8221; (2 Pet 3:16). The thorn-proverb is not merely academic — mishandled wisdom injures.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The theme: the archer who wounds everyone indiscriminately — one who hires a fool or passerby. The promiscuous employment of the unvetted produces indiscriminate damage. Jesus&#8217; parable of the wheat and weeds (Matt 13:24-30) touches the same issue: the indiscriminate removal of weeds before harvest damages the wheat. Wisdom in employment, in discipleship selection, in entrusting responsibility — Christ himself &#8220;chose twelve&#8221; (John 6:70) after a night of prayer (Luke 6:12-13), demonstrating the discernment that Proverbs 26:10 assumes is possible and necessary.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A direct anticipation: &#8220;Like a dog that returns to its vomit is a fool who repeats his folly.&#8221; Peter quotes this directly in 2 Pet 2:22 as a warning against false teachers who return to their former way of life after professing faith. The image is as vivid in its NT application as in its Proverbs source: the one who has been cleansed and returns to defilement is doing the most self-defeating possible thing. Christ&#8217;s healing of the man at the pool includes the warning: &#8220;Stop sinning or something worse may happen to you&#8221; (John 5:14) — the implied alternative is the dog-and-vomit pattern.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The theme: more hope for a fool than for the man wise in his own eyes. The self-sufficiency of perceived wisdom is diagnosed by Jesus as the most dangerous spiritual condition: the Pharisee who is &#8220;confident of his own righteousness&#8221; (Luke 18:9) is further from the kingdom than the tax collector who knows his need. &#8220;It is not the healthy who need a doctor, but the sick&#8221; (Matt 9:12) — the person wise in their own eyes has no sense of need and therefore no access to the remedy that Christ offers. The fool can receive; the self-wise cannot.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theme: the sluggard&#8217;s implausible excuse — the lion in the road. The elaborate self-justification for inaction (a lion! I cannot go out!) is the pattern of excuse-making that the invited guests use in Jesus&#8217; parable of the Great Banquet: &#8220;I just bought a field&#8230; I have just bought five yoke of oxen&#8230; I just got married&#8221; (Luke 14:18-20). The excuses may be more plausible than the lion, but the structure is identical: any pretext to avoid the urgent call. The sluggard&#8217;s lion is the emblem of all the invented obstacles to responding to Wisdom.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The theme: the door turning on its hinges — the sluggard turning on his bed. The futility of motion-without-progress: the door turns but goes nowhere; the sluggard turns but accomplishes nothing. The warning against spiritual lethargy that produces only the appearance of movement without actual progress is echoed in Revelation&#8217;s warning to Laodicea: &#8220;you are neither cold nor hot — I wish you were either one or the other!&#8221; (Rev 3:15). The door-on-hinges sluggard is the emblem of the lukewarm church that turns without advancing.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The theme: the sluggard who cannot bring the hand from the dish to the mouth. The absolute minimum of self-provision — feeding oneself — is too much effort for the fully developed sluggard. The spiritual application is the person who has access to the bread of life but cannot bring themselves to receive it: &#8220;you refuse to come to me to have life&#8221; (John 5:40). The effort required to receive what is freely offered is minimal; the sluggard represents those for whom even this minimum is not taken. Christ&#8217;s offer requires reception; the refusal to reach is its own judgment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The theme: the sluggard wiser in his own eyes than seven who can give sensible answers. The combination of sloth and arrogance is the lethal pair: not merely lazy but unteachable. The Pharisees who &#8220;strain out a gnat but swallow a camel&#8221; (Matt 23:24) — supremely confident in their own understanding while missing the weightier matters of the law — are the spiritual equivalent of the sluggard-wise-in-his-own-eyes. Self-satisfied incompetence is the most difficult condition for wisdom to address.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The theme: grabbing a dog by the ears — meddling in a quarrel not your own. The danger of inserting yourself into a conflict you have no standing in — you end up holding an angry dog you cannot safely release. Jude 9 applies a related principle: &#8220;Michael did not dare to bring a slanderous accusation against Satan himself.&#8221; The wisdom of not overreaching in conflicts is demonstrated in Christ&#8217;s own ministry: &#8220;Man, who appointed me a judge or an arbiter between you?&#8221; (Luke 12:14) — the Son of God knowing when to refuse the role that others wanted to assign him.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theme: the madman throwing firebrands and arrows and death. The image of chaotic, indiscriminate destruction as the emblem of the deceiver of v19 — malice dressed as play. Jesus warns against the same pattern in the religious sphere: false prophets who appear in sheep&#8217;s clothing but inwardly are &#8220;ferocious wolves&#8221; (Matt 7:15). The firebrand-thrower who claims to be joking is a type of the deceiver whose &#8220;harmless&#8221; falsehoods produce catastrophic consequences.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The theme: the deceiver who says &#8220;I was only joking.&#8221; The denial of destructive intent after the damage is done — the claim that harmful speech or action was play. Judas&#8217; betrayal has this structure: the kiss, the greeting, the social form of friendship deployed as a weapon (Matt 26:48-49). The &#8220;I was only joking&#8221; is the sophisticated deceiver&#8217;s version of Judas&#8217; &#8220;Rabbi&#8221; — familiar language weaponized against the one addressed. Christ&#8217;s response to Judas — &#8220;do what you came for&#8221; (Matt 26:50) — refuses to participate in the pretense.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: without gossip a quarrel dies down — like fire without wood. The cessation of fuel ends the fire; the cessation of gossip ends the strife. This is the structural insight behind James&#8217;s teaching on the tongue as a spark that sets a forest on fire (Jas 3:5-6). Christ&#8217;s call to be &#8220;peacemakers&#8221; (Matt 5:9) involves this same principle applied positively: removing the fuel of slander and gossip allows the fire of conflict to die rather than spread. Peacemaking is partly the active work of withdrawing combustible material.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The theme: the quarrelsome man as charcoal to fire — kindling strife. The complement of v20: the person whose character is incendiary adds fuel wherever they go. Paul&#8217;s description of the fruit of the sinful nature includes &#8220;discord, jealousy, fits of rage, selfish ambition, dissensions, factions&#8221; (Gal 5:20) — the cluster of fire-kindling qualities that characterize life outside of Christ. The fruit of the Spirit (Gal 5:22-23) produces the opposite: love, peace, patience — qualities that cool rather than kindle.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The theme: gossip as delicacies that sink into the inner chambers. The same saying as 18:8 — the repetition signals its importance. The irresistible pleasure of gossip that lodges in memory and corrupts judgment is the dark mirror of the word that Christ plants in the heart: &#8220;The seed on good soil stands for those with a noble and good heart, who hear the word, retain it, and by persevering produce a crop&#8221; (Luke 8:15). Both gossip and the gospel descend to the inner chambers; the question is what kind of seed takes root there.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The theme: fervent lips with a wicked heart — silver glaze on a clay pot. The beautiful exterior concealing an inferior interior is one of Jesus&#8217; consistent targets: &#8220;Woe to you, teachers of the law and Pharisees, you hypocrites! You are like whitewashed tombs, which look beautiful on the outside but on the inside are full of the bones of the dead&#8221; (Matt 23:27). The silver-glazed clay pot of Proverbs 26:23 is the OT anticipation of the whitewashed tomb — beautiful surface, corrupt interior.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The theme: the hater who disguises hatred with smooth lips while storing up deceit within. The internal-external disconnect — surface speech contradicting internal state — is what Jesus describes as hypocritical wickedness (Matt 23:27-28: &#8220;inside you are full of hypocrisy and wickedness&#8221;). Christ&#8217;s consistent refusal of the smooth-lips approach to social interaction — his directness, his refusal to flatter, his willingness to say hard things to powerful people — stands as the contrast to the hater who masks with pleasantness.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Do not believe him&#8221; — seven abominations in his heart despite gracious speech. The warning against the appearance of grace that masks hatred connects to Jesus&#8217; warning: &#8220;Watch out for false prophets. They come to you in sheep&#8217;s clothing, but inwardly they are ferocious wolves. By their fruit you will recognize them&#8221; (Matt 7:15-16). The seven abominations concealed in the gracious speaker&#8217;s heart are the invisible fruit that Christ&#8217;s warning prepares the disciple to look for.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The theme: the hidden hatred exposed before the assembly. The concealment that seemed permanent is ultimately uncovered. The eschatological disclosure applies: &#8220;There is nothing concealed that will not be disclosed, or hidden that will not be made known&#8221; (Matt 10:26; Luke 12:2). Christ&#8217;s resurrection functions as the ultimate exposure of the hidden evil of his condemnation: &#8220;you disowned the Holy and Righteous One&#8230; but God raised him from the dead&#8221; (Acts 3:14-15). The hidden wickedness behind the gracious surface is exposed before the assembly of all creation.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The theme: whoever digs a pit falls into it; whoever rolls a stone has it roll back. The self-entrapment of wickedness — the plot that backfires on the plotter — is the structural pattern of the crucifixion and resurrection. Those who plotted to destroy Jesus fell into their own trap: &#8220;he was not abandoned to the realm of the dead, nor did his body see decay&#8221; (Acts 2:31). The stone they rolled to the tomb (Matt 27:60) was rolled away (Matt 28:2). The pit dug for the Righteous One became the tomb he exited. The Proverbs principle of retributive reversal is enacted at its fullest in the Easter event.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The theme: the lying tongue hates those it hurts; the flattering mouth works ruin. The diagnostic of hatred concealed in speech — lying as an expression of hatred, flattery as an instrument of ruin — reveals the destructive character of deceptive communication. The NT applies this to false teaching: &#8220;with flattery they exploit you&#8221; (2 Pet 2:3). Christ as the one who speaks truth even when it costs him — &#8220;I told you the truth, that is why you do not believe me&#8221; (John 8:45) — is the counter to every lying tongue and flattering mouth. His speech is love that costs, not flattery that ruins.</p>"
  },
  "27": {
    "1": "<p>The theme: do not boast about tomorrow — you do not know what a day may bring. The humility regarding the future that Proverbs commends is taken up by James as an apostolic instruction: &#8220;Why, you do not even know what will happen tomorrow&#8230; instead, you ought to say, &#8216;If it is the Lord&#8217;s will, we will live and do this or that&#8217;&#8221; (Jas 4:13-15). Christ lives the principle perfectly: his submission to &#8220;not my will, but yours be done&#8221; (Luke 22:42) is the fullest expression of not boasting about tomorrow but entrusting it to the Father.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The theme: let someone else praise you, not your own mouth. The self-commendation principle: genuine worth is established by external recognition, not self-assertion. Paul applies this directly: &#8220;it is not the one who commends himself who is approved, but the one whom the Lord commends&#8221; (2 Cor 10:18). Christ himself receives praise not from his own advocacy but from the Father&#8217;s declaration: &#8220;This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased&#8221; (Matt 3:17; 17:5). The Father&#8217;s voice at the baptism and transfiguration is the ultimate fulfillment of &#8220;let someone else praise you.&#8221;</p>",
    "3": "<p>The theme: the fool&#8217;s anger heavier than stone and sand. The excess weight of the fool&#8217;s disproportionate anger is the OT observation about the exhausting nature of dealing with irrational rage. James connects anger to destructive outcomes: &#8220;human anger does not produce the righteousness that God desires&#8221; (Jas 1:20). Christ himself displays righteous anger (John 2:15; Mark 3:5) — but it is calibrated, purposeful, and directed at the right objects. The fool&#8217;s anger is the weight that crushes; Christ&#8217;s anger is the force that cleanses.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The theme: wrath is cruel and anger is overwhelming, but who can stand before envy? The escalating dangers of passion — wrath, anger, envy — with envy as the worst because it is the most corrosive and most hidden. The chief priests handed Jesus over &#8220;out of envy&#8221; (Matt 27:18; Mark 15:10) — the root of the passion narrative is identified by Pilate himself as envy. The envy that no one can stand before was the force behind the crucifixion. Christ enters the full force of human destructive passion and absorbs it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The theme: open rebuke is better than hidden love. The faithful wound that honest correction inflicts is preferable to the comfortable silence of unexpressed love. Jesus embodies this: his rebukes of the disciples (Matt 16:23: &#8220;Get behind me, Satan&#8221;; Mark 9:19: &#8220;unbelieving generation&#8221;), his confrontations with the Pharisees, his letters to the seven churches (Rev 2-3: &#8220;I have this against you&#8221;) are all expressions of the open rebuke that Proverbs identifies as the superior form of love. Silence in the face of error is not love but its abdication.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A shadow: &#8220;The wounds of a friend can be trusted, but an enemy&#8217;s kisses are lavish and false.&#8221; The enemy&#8217;s false kiss is enacted at Gethsemane when Judas greets Jesus with &#8220;Rabbi!&#8221; and kisses him as the signal to the arresting party (Matt 26:48-49; Luke 22:47-48). The lavish, false kiss of Proverbs 27:6 is perfectly realized in the traitor&#8217;s kiss — the most intimate greeting weaponized as the instrument of betrayal. Jesus&#8217; response — &#8220;Judas, are you betraying the Son of Man with a kiss?&#8221; (Luke 22:48) — unmasks the false kiss with precise wisdom.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The theme: the full person despises honey; to the hungry every bitter thing is sweet. The hunger that transforms bitterness into sweetness is the experiential basis of the beatitude: &#8220;Blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they will be filled&#8221; (Matt 5:6). The person who hungers for what God provides finds that even difficult truths, demanding commands, and costly discipleship have a sweetness that the satisfied person cannot taste. Christ himself is the honey — despised by the full, longed for by the hungry.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The theme: the man who wanders from his home is like a bird that flees its nest. The homelessness that results from self-imposed wandering — cutting the ties of belonging without arriving anywhere. The parable of the prodigal son (Luke 15:11-32) is this image expanded: the son who leaves the father&#8217;s house is the bird fleeing the nest, exposed to predators and weather. Christ comes to restore the wanderer home: &#8220;Father, I have sinned against heaven and against you&#8221; (Luke 15:21) — the return from wandering is the return to the Father that Christ makes possible.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The theme: oil and perfume bring joy to the heart; so does a friend&#8217;s earnest counsel. The physical and relational sources of joy — anointing oil and faithful friendship — are combined as equals. The anointing of Jesus (Mark 14:3-9; Luke 7:36-50) combines both: the physical anointing with costly perfume and the relational intimacy of the one who loves much. The friend&#8217;s earnest counsel finds its fullest expression in Christ&#8217;s promise: &#8220;I no longer call you servants&#8230; Instead, I have called you friends&#8221; (John 15:15) — friendship that includes the full counsel of all he has heard from the Father.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The theme: do not forsake your friend or your father&#8217;s friend; a neighbor nearby is better than a brother far away. The priority of present, reliable relationships over distant kin connections reflects the wisdom of covenantal nearness. Christ redefines family around responsiveness to God: &#8220;Whoever does the will of my Father in heaven is my brother and sister and mother&#8221; (Matt 12:50). The neighbor who is near and faithful is the image of the new community that Christ creates — those who are near to him in discipleship are his true family.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The theme: &#8220;Be wise, my son, and gladden my heart, so I may have a word for whoever taunts me.&#8221; The father&#8217;s stake in the son&#8217;s wisdom — the son&#8217;s conduct determines the father&#8217;s ability to respond to accusers. The Father&#8217;s vindication through the Son&#8217;s wisdom is the heavenly pattern: &#8220;The Father loves the Son and has placed everything in his hands&#8221; (John 3:35); &#8220;I always do what pleases him&#8221; (John 8:29). Christ&#8217;s perfect obedience gladdens the Father and equips the Father to answer every accuser. The proverb is fulfilled in the perfect Son.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The theme: the prudent person sees danger and hides; the simple walk on and suffer for it. The foresight of wisdom — anticipating consequences and acting accordingly — is the quality Jesus expects of his disciples: &#8220;Suppose a king is about to go to war&#8230; Won&#8217;t he first sit down and consider whether he is able?&#8221; (Luke 14:31). Christ himself demonstrates this foresight throughout his ministry: &#8220;no one takes my life from me, but I lay it down of my own accord&#8221; (John 10:18) — he sees the danger not as a fatal surprise but as the appointed moment to act.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The theme: taking the garment of one who puts up security for a stranger. The commercial-risk warning (cf. 6:1-5; 20:16) — taking collateral against the imprudent guarantor. The legal vocabulary of surety and pledge has a theological dimension in the NT: Christ becomes the guarantee of a better covenant: &#8220;Jesus has become the guarantor of a better covenant&#8221; (Heb 7:22, <em>ĕgguos</em>). Christ is the surety who does not fail — the one who pledges himself on behalf of those who cannot pay their debt and makes full payment through the cross.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The theme: blessing the neighbor loudly in the morning is counted a curse. The performative blessing that calls attention to itself rather than genuinely serving the neighbor — the social virtue that is actually selfishness dressed as generosity. Jesus&#8217; Sermon on the Mount targets exactly this: &#8220;Be careful not to practice your righteousness in front of others to be seen by them&#8221; (Matt 6:1). The ostentatious morning blessing is the OT equivalent of trumpeting almsgiving — a curse because it is a performance of virtue rather than its substance.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The theme: the constant dripping on a rainy day and a quarrelsome person — alike in unrelenting, wearing distress. The comparison communicates both the constancy and the weariness. In contrast, Christ&#8217;s presence is described as rest: &#8220;Come to me, all you who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest&#8221; (Matt 11:28). The relentless drip of the quarrelsome person is the anti-rest; Christ is the anti-drip — not a constant irritant but a constant renewal. The contrast is experienced by those who know both.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The theme: restraining the quarrelsome person is like restraining the wind or grasping oil. The futility of containing what will not be contained by force — the quarrelsome person&#8217;s strife flows through every attempted barrier. The same futility applies to attempting to contain the gospel by force: &#8220;we cannot help speaking about what we have seen and heard&#8221; (Acts 4:20). The wind that cannot be contained in Proverbs 27:16 becomes the Spirit who &#8220;blows wherever it pleases&#8221; (John 3:8) — equally uncontainable, but life-giving rather than destructive.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The theme: iron sharpening iron — one person sharpening another. The mutual formation that genuine relationship produces: both parties are changed by the friction of honest encounter. The NT community is described in terms of this mutual sharpening: &#8220;And let us consider how we may spur one another on toward love and good deeds, not giving up meeting together&#8221; (Heb 10:24-25). Christ himself is the primary iron — his disciples are sharpened by their encounter with him. The disciples who follow Jesus are formed and sharpened through his demanding, honest, loving interaction with them.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The theme: whoever tends the fig tree eats its fruit; whoever looks after his master is honored. The faithfulness-and-reward structure is used by Jesus directly in the parable of the talents: &#8220;Well done, good and faithful servant&#8230; Come and share your master&#8217;s happiness&#8221; (Matt 25:21). The vine-dresser who tends the vine is honored with its fruit; the disciple who abides in Christ (John 15:1-5) bears fruit — the honoring of the faithful servant is the pattern that Christ both describes and fulfills as the faithful Son who is &#8220;the heir of all things&#8221; (Heb 1:2).</p>",
    "19": "<p>A revelation of God: &#8220;As water reflects a face, so one person&#8217;s heart reflects another&#8217;s.&#8221; The water-mirror that shows you yourself is the image of the relationship that reveals character through reflection. Hebrews applies this relational-reflection principle to Christ: he is &#8220;the radiance of God&#8217;s glory and the exact representation of his being (<em>charaktēr tēs hypostaseōs autou</em>)&#8221; (Heb 1:3). The Son is the perfect water-reflection of the Father — seeing the Son is seeing the Father (John 14:9). The Proverbs image of mutual human reflection is the shadow of the perfect divine self-reflection in the Son.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The theme: Sheol and Abaddon are never satisfied — nor are the eyes of man. The insatiable appetite of death and the insatiable appetite of human desire are placed in parallel. Christ overcomes the first: &#8220;I hold the keys of death and Hades&#8221; (Rev 1:18); &#8220;Death has been swallowed up in victory&#8221; (1 Cor 15:54). And he addresses the second: &#8220;I am the bread of life; whoever comes to me will never go hungry, and whoever believes in me will never be thirsty&#8221; (John 6:35). The never-satisfied Sheol and the never-satisfied eyes are both answered in Christ — one by conquest, the other by satisfaction.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The theme: the crucible and furnace test metals; a man is tested by praise. The human analogue to the metallurgical test: how a person responds to praise reveals their character. James warns of the testing that comes from prosperity as well as adversity: &#8220;the testing of your faith produces perseverance&#8221; (Jas 1:3). Jesus himself is &#8220;tested in every way, just as we are, yet he did not sin&#8221; (Heb 4:15) — including the test of public praise (the triumphal entry, John 6:15 where the crowd wants to make him king). Christ responds to praise without being captured by it.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The theme: grinding the fool in a mortar does not remove the folly. The incorrigibility of settled folly — no amount of painful correction removes what is constitutively embedded. Paul acknowledges a comparable spiritual reality: some are given over to a depraved mind (Rom 1:28). Yet the gospel is the counter-claim: &#8220;if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come&#8221; (2 Cor 5:17). What the mortar cannot accomplish — the removal of folly — the new birth can. Christ is the answer to the fool-in-the-mortar problem: transformation rather than correction of what is constitutively broken.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The theme: know the condition of your flocks — give careful attention to your herds. The responsible shepherd who knows each animal is the OT pattern that Christ claims for himself: &#8220;I am the good shepherd; I know my sheep and my sheep know me&#8221; (John 10:14). The good shepherd&#8217;s intimate knowledge of his flock — &#8220;he calls his own sheep by name&#8221; (John 10:3) — is the fulfilment of the careful herd-attention that Proverbs 27:23 recommends. Christ is the perfect shepherd who knows &#8220;the condition of his flocks&#8221; with a completeness no human shepherd achieves.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The theme: riches do not last forever; nor does the crown endure to all generations. The transience of earthly wealth and power is the backdrop against which the eternal kingdom is set. Hebrews contrasts the temporary Levitical priesthood with Christ&#8217;s permanent priesthood: &#8220;Jesus lives forever, he has a permanent priesthood&#8221; (Heb 7:24). Every earthly crown that does not endure to all generations is the shadow of the one crown that does: &#8220;the crown of righteousness&#8221; (2 Tim 4:8) given to those who have longed for Christ&#8217;s appearing — the crown that does not fade (1 Pet 5:4).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The theme: the cyclical renewal of grass and growth — the ongoing order of creation that sustains the flocks. The agricultural cycle in vv25-27 describes the providential order of creation that provides food, clothing, and sustenance. Jesus grounds his teaching on anxiety in exactly this pattern: &#8220;Look at the birds of the air; they do not sow or reap&#8230; yet your heavenly Father feeds them&#8221; (Matt 6:26). The seasonal provision of Proverbs 27:25 is the OT observation that Jesus cites as the basis for trusting the Father&#8217;s provision.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The theme: the lambs for clothing, the goats for the field. The flock as the source of both clothing and capital in the agricultural economy. The sheep provide not merely food but covering — an image that runs through the NT: the church is clothed through Christ&#8217;s provision (Rev 19:8: &#8220;fine linen&#8230; the righteous acts of God&#8217;s holy people&#8221;). The lambs that provide clothing in Proverbs 27:26 are the natural image for the Lamb of God whose sacrifice clothes the saints in the righteousness they cannot produce themselves.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The theme: the sufficiency of goats&#8217; milk — enough food for household and servants. The agricultural section concludes with the provision of sufficiency: enough, not abundance — the same theme as Agur&#8217;s prayer (30:8: &#8220;give me neither poverty nor riches&#8221;). Christ teaches the same sufficiency-theology: &#8220;Give us today our daily bread&#8221; (Matt 6:11). The enough-for-the-household that the flock provides is the natural image of the daily provision that the Father gives to those who seek his kingdom first (Matt 6:33). Sufficient provision through faithful stewardship is the agricultural form of kingdom-economics.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(c, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'proverbs', c)
    total = sum(len(vs) for vs in PROVERBS.values())
    print(f'proverbs mkt-christ: {total} entries written (ch25-27)')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
